B 1346) slices through the waters of Prince William Sound at full speed.jpg|60px]] || [[USCGC Roanoke Island (WPB-1346)|''Roanoke Island'' (WPB-1346)]] || || ||transferred to Costa Rica, renamed ''Gen. Jose M. Canas Escamilla''\n|-\n| || [[USCGC Pea Island (WPB-1347)|''Pea Island'' (WPB-1347)]] || || ||purchased by Sea Shepherd, renamed MY ''Farley Mowat''\n|-\n| [[File:USCGC Knight island.jpg|99px]] || [[USCGC Knight Island (WPB-1348)|''Knight Island'' (WPB-1348)]] || || ||\n|-\n| [[File:USCGC Galveston Island - 170214-G-CA140-1001.jpg|99px]] || [[USCGC Galveston Island (WPB-1349)|''Galveston Island'' (WPB-1349)]] || || ||\n|}\n\n==Gallery==\n{{Cleanup gallery|date=April 2017}}\n<gallery>\nFile:Sanibel 1.jpg|USCG ''Sanibel'' moored in Boston Harbor\n\nFile:USCG WPBs transported to Mediterranean.jpg|Four WPBs transported to the Mediterranean aboard MV ''BBC Spain''\n\nFile:120405-G-RS249-005-USCG responds to Japanese vessel in Gulf of Alaska.jpg|USCGC {{USCGC|Anacapa|WPB-1335|2}} sinks derelict {{ship||Ryou-Un Maru||2}} fishing vessel with fire hose, 5 April 2012.\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* USCG {{sclass2-|Marine Protector|coastal patrol boat|1}}\n* USCG [[Short Range Prosecutor]]\n* USCG {{sclass2-|Cape|cutter|2}}\n* USCG {{sclass2-|Sentinel|cutter|2}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat|Island class cutters}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928121120/http://www.icgsdeepwater.com/resources/video/MATAGORDA.mpg Video of the Matagorda deploying and retrieving her Short Range Prosecutor pursuit launch at speed].\n*[http://www.uscg.mil/deepwater/system/123.htm Official description of the conversion from 110 to 123 feet.]\n\n{{Island class cutter}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Island-class patrol boat}}\n[[Category:Patrol vessels of the United States]]\n[[Category:Island-class patrol boats| ]]\n[[Category:Patrol boat classes]]\n[[Category:1980s ships]]\n", "name_user": "Illegitimate Barrister", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Island-class_patrol_boat"}
{"title_page": "John Fury", "text_new": "{{short description|British boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = John Fury\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = John Fury\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1964|5|22}} <ref name=\"BoxRec\" />\n| birth_place = [[Galway]], Ireland\n| known_for   = [[Professional boxing]]\n| height      =  1.91m\n| children    = [[Tyson Fury]], [[Tommy Fury]], Shane Fury, Hughie Fury\n}}\n'''John Fury''' (born 22 May 1964) is an Irish-British boxing cornerman and former [[professional boxer]]<ref name=\"BoxRec\">{{Cite web|url=https://boxrec.com/en/proboxer/27680|title=BoxRec John Fury {{!}} BoxRec|website=boxrec.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> and bare-knuckle fighter. He is best known for being the father to his well-known sons, namely two-time heavyweight boxing world champion [[Tyson Fury]], as well as professional boxer and reality television star [[Tommy Fury]]. He is also uncle to heavyweight boxer [[Hughie Fury]].\n\n==Background==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2020}}\nFury comes from a long lineage of bare-knuckle fighters, owing to his traveller roots. Alongside a professional boxing career, Fury has also said that he was involved in many bare-knuckle fights.\n\nFury has reportedly stated that the fights he did have were \"usually over within seconds\", and that he \"wasn't an especially big puncher\", but that he would \"not stop swinging until they were out cold, I\u2019d hit them with fists, elbows, head, teeth and feet until they dropped and give best [surrendered]\".\n\n==Boxing career==\n\nFury's professional boxing career spanned 8 years, beginning in April 1987 and ending in June 1995. In total, he was involved in 13 bouts.<ref name=\"BoxRec\" />\n\nHe made his professional debut on 28 April 1987 when he fought Adam Fogerty in [[Halifax, West Yorkshire]]. He went on to win his next 6 fights until a draw with David Hopkins in [[Helsinki]] on 13 February 1989.<ref name=\"BoxRec\" />\n\nHis last professional fight was reportedly against Steve Garber at the G-Mex Centre in Manchester in 1995.<ref name=\"BoxRec\" />\n\n==Public image==\n\nFury is well known in the boxing world and has been involved in many high-profile situations whilst supporting his son [[Tyson Fury|Tyson]]. After Tyson Fury [[Wladimir Klitschko vs. Tyson Fury|defeated]] reigning 11-year champion [[Wladimir Klitschko]] in [[Dusseldorf]] on November 27, 2015, John Fury heavily criticised the media for the lack of faith they placed in his son before the fight. In the much-publicised speech at a post-fight press conference, Fury instructed the media to \"stop being yes men\" and ordered everybody in the room to give his son a [[standing ovation]] for his achievement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/klitschko-vs-fury/news/33472/10085623/tyson-furys-father-in-fine-form-after-world-title-triumph|title=Tyson Fury's father John delivers rant at press conference {{!}} |website=SkySports.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nIn the buildup to the Wilder rematch, Fury was involved in a heated dispute with former heavyweight boxer [[David Haye]] over his sons chances before the fight. Fury stated that Wilder would 'crack' given that Tyson is no longer \"as weak as a kitten\" unlike in their previous controversial draw. He told BT Sport \"\u2018A man when he\u2019s pressured and he\u2019s in a hard time, he\u2019ll crack at the seams\u2019, before offering Haye a \u00a3100,000 bet on whether he would be proven correct.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/02/08/david-haye-john-fury-clash-deontay-wilder-rematch-tyson-fury-12204525/|title=David Haye and John Fury clash over Deontay Wilder rematch with Tyson Fury {{!}} |website=metro.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nMore recently, Fury appeared in the ITV documentary series 'Tyson Fury: The Gypsy King' detailing the road to his sons rematch with former champion [[Deontay Wilder]].<ref name=\"talksport.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://talksport.com/sport/boxing/678851/boxing-news-watch-john-fury-balls-tyson-fury-deontay-wilder/|title=Watch as John Fury grabs his crotch and shouts, \u2018That\u2019s what come out of these balls,\u2019 after Tyson Fury knocks down Deontay Wilder {{!}} |website=talkSport|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Fury appears many times but most notably in one of the final scenes showing his live reaction to the fight as he watched on a television at the BT studios.<ref name=\"talksport.com\"/>\n\n==Media appearances==\n\nFury has appeared on multiple British television broadcasters, including live shows, pre-recorded programmes and documentaries. On 20 February 2020, he appeared on ITV show '[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]' before his sons rematch against Deontay Wilder, reassuring viewers that \"Tyson is at his strongest now\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/thismorning|title=John Fury believes Tyson Fury is at his Strongest Now {{!}} |website=ITV)|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 February, he appeared on breakfast television show '[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]' discussing his sons mental health, as well as his view on his younger son Tommy Fury's involvement in the ITV2 reality television series [[Love Island (2015 TV series)|Love Island]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/goodmorningbritain|title=Tyson Fury's Dad talks the Boxer's Mental Health & Tommy Fury on Love Island {{!}} |website=GMB|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = John Fury\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = John Fury\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1964|5|22}} <ref name=\"BoxRec\" />\n| birth_place = [[Galway]], Ireland\n| known_for   = [[Professional boxing]]\n| height      =  1.91m\n| children    = [[Tyson Fury]], [[Tommy Fury]], Shane Fury, Hughie Fury\n}}\n'''John Fury''' (born 22 May 1964) is a Irish-British boxing cornerman and former [[professional boxer]]<ref name=\"BoxRec\">{{Cite web|url=https://boxrec.com/en/proboxer/27680|title=BoxRec John Fury {{!}} BoxRec|website=boxrec.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> and bare-knuckle fighter. He is best known for being the father to his well-known sons, namely two-time heavyweight boxing world champion [[Tyson Fury]], as well as professional boxer and reality television star [[Tommy Fury]]. He is also uncle to heavyweight boxer [[Hughie Fury]].\n\n==Background==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2020}}\nFury comes from a long lineage of bare-knuckle fighters, owing to his traveller roots. Alongside a professional boxing career, Fury has also said that he was involved in many bare-knuckle fights.\n\nFury has reportedly stated that the fights he did have were \"usually over within seconds\", and that he \"wasn't an especially big puncher\", but that he would \"not stop swinging until they were out cold, I\u2019d hit them with fists, elbows, head, teeth and feet until they dropped and give best [surrendered]\".\n\n==Boxing career==\n\nFury's professional boxing career spanned 8 years, beginning in April 1987 and ending in June 1995. In total, he was involved in 13 bouts.<ref name=\"BoxRec\" />\n\nHe made his professional debut on 28 April 1987 when he fought Adam Fogerty in [[Halifax, West Yorkshire]]. He went on to win his next 6 fights until a draw with David Hopkins in [[Helsinki]] on 13 February 1989.<ref name=\"BoxRec\" />\n\nHis last professional fight was reportedly against Steve Garber at the G-Mex Centre in Manchester in 1995.<ref name=\"BoxRec\" />\n\n==Public image==\n\nFury is well known in the boxing world and has been involved in many high-profile situations whilst supporting his son [[Tyson Fury|Tyson]]. After Tyson Fury [[Wladimir Klitschko vs. Tyson Fury|defeated]] reigning 11-year champion [[Wladimir Klitschko]] in [[Dusseldorf]] on November 27, 2015, John Fury heavily criticised the media for the lack of faith they placed in his son before the fight. In the much-publicised speech at a post-fight press conference, Fury instructed the media to \"stop being yes men\" and ordered everybody in the room to give his son a [[standing ovation]] for his achievement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/klitschko-vs-fury/news/33472/10085623/tyson-furys-father-in-fine-form-after-world-title-triumph|title=Tyson Fury's father John delivers rant at press conference {{!}} |website=SkySports.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nIn the buildup to the Wilder rematch, Fury was involved in a heated dispute with former heavyweight boxer [[David Haye]] over his sons chances before the fight. Fury stated that Wilder would 'crack' given that Tyson is no longer \"as weak as a kitten\" unlike in their previous controversial draw. He told BT Sport \"\u2018A man when he\u2019s pressured and he\u2019s in a hard time, he\u2019ll crack at the seams\u2019, before offering Haye a \u00a3100,000 bet on whether he would be proven correct.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/02/08/david-haye-john-fury-clash-deontay-wilder-rematch-tyson-fury-12204525/|title=David Haye and John Fury clash over Deontay Wilder rematch with Tyson Fury {{!}} |website=metro.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nMore recently, Fury appeared in the ITV documentary series 'Tyson Fury: The Gypsy King' detailing the road to his sons rematch with former champion [[Deontay Wilder]].<ref name=\"talksport.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://talksport.com/sport/boxing/678851/boxing-news-watch-john-fury-balls-tyson-fury-deontay-wilder/|title=Watch as John Fury grabs his crotch and shouts, \u2018That\u2019s what come out of these balls,\u2019 after Tyson Fury knocks down Deontay Wilder {{!}} |website=talkSport|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> Fury appears many times but most notably in one of the final scenes showing his live reaction to the fight as he watched on a television at the BT studios.<ref name=\"talksport.com\"/>\n\n==Media appearances==\n\nFury has appeared on multiple British television broadcasters, including live shows, pre-recorded programmes and documentaries. On 20 February 2020, he appeared on ITV show '[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]' before his sons rematch against Deontay Wilder, reassuring viewers that \"Tyson is at his strongest now\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/thismorning|title=John Fury believes Tyson Fury is at his Strongest Now {{!}} |website=ITV)|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 February, he appeared on breakfast television show '[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]' discussing his sons mental health, as well as his view on his younger son Tommy Fury's involvement in the ITV2 reality television series [[Love Island (2015 TV series)|Love Island]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/goodmorningbritain|title=Tyson Fury's Dad talks the Boxer's Mental Health & Tommy Fury on Love Island {{!}} |website=GMB|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Fury"}
{"title_page": "Toivo Mikael Kivim\u00e4ki", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    =\n| name                = Toivo Mikael Kivim\u00e4ki\n| honorific-suffix    =\n| image               = Toivo Kivim\u00e4ki.png\n| imagesize           = 200px\n| office              = [[List of Prime Ministers of Finland|13th]] [[Prime Minister of Finland]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Governments in chronological order|url=http://valtioneuvosto.fi/en/government/history/governments-and-ministers/report/-/r/v2|publisher=Finnish government (Valtioneuvosto)|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n| term_start          = 14 December 1932\n| term_end            = 7 October 1936\n| president           = [[Pehr Evind Svinhufvud]]\n| predecessor         = [[Juho Sunila]]\n| successor           = [[Ky\u00f6sti Kallio]]\n| birth_date          = 5 June 1886\n| birth_place         = [[Tarvasjoki]], [[Finland]]\n| death_date          =  {{Death date and age|df=yes|1968|5|6|1886|6|5}}\n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[National Progressive Party (Finland)|National Progressive Party]]\n}}\n'''Toivo Mikael Kivim\u00e4ki''' (5 June 1886 &ndash; 6 May 1968), [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]], was head of the department of [[Civil law (legal system)|civil law]] at [[Helsinki University]] 1931&ndash;1956, [[Prime Minister of Finland]] 1932&ndash;1936, and [[Finland]]'s [[Envoy (title)|Envoy]] to [[Berlin]] 1940&ndash;1944.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.valtioneuvosto.fi/hakemisto/ministerikortisto/ministeritiedot.asp?nro=161 |title=Ministerikortisto |publisher=Valtioneuvosto }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== Early career ===\nHe was elected as member of the Parliament for terms 1922, 1924-1927 and 1929\u20131940. \nBefore prime ministership, Kivim\u00e4ki served as [[Minister of the Interior (Finland)|Minister of the Interior]] 1928-1929<ref>{{cite web|url=http://valtioneuvosto.fi/tietoa/historiaa/hallitukset-ja-ministerit/raportti/-/r/v9l/16 |title=Council of State - Ministers of Interior |publisher=Valtioneuvosto.fi |accessdate=27 December 2017 }}</ref> and [[Minister of Justice (Finland)|Minister of Justice]] 1931\u20131932.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://valtioneuvosto.fi/tietoa/historiaa/hallitukset-ja-ministerit/raportti/-/r/v9l/9 |title=Council of State - Ministers of Justice |publisher=Valtioneuvosto.fi |accessdate=27 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\n=== After WWII ===\nIn 1946, Kivim\u00e4ki together with half-a-dozen other leading politicians were put on \"[[war-responsibility trials]]\" executed under pressure from the [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] victors in [[World War II]]. Kivim\u00e4ki was sentenced to five years in prison after being found responsible for the [[Continuation War]]. After Finland signed the [[Paris Peace Treaties, 1947]], and the  Finno&ndash;Soviet [[Finno-Soviet Treaty of 1948|Agreement of Friendship, Cooperation, and Mutual Assistance]], 1948, the international situation was deemed somewhat stabilized, and Kivim\u00e4ki was pardoned. He returned to his career in academia.\n\n=== Legacy ===\nAs with all politicians connected with the Continuation War, Kivim\u00e4ki was for decades seen in a somewhat critical light. During the era of [[finlandization]], many prominent Finns expressed themselves cautiously on such subjects in order not to disturb sensitive Allied victors of the war; a cautiousness that without doubt influenced Finland's post-war generation's understanding and views.\n\n* As Prime Minister, Kivim\u00e4ki headed Finland's (until 1987) most long-lived [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]], aiming at stabilizing the turbulent politics in Finland after the semi-[[fascist]] [[M\u00e4nts\u00e4l\u00e4 Rebellion]] had been put down.\n* He achieved the reversal of Finland's foreign policy into a [[neutralist]] pro-[[Scandinavia]]n stance, and a Swedish rapprochement, that may well have been prepared for in the most initiated circles, but that in the contemporary tense phase of the [[language strife in Finland]] was not at all easy to explain to the public opinion.\n* As an Envoy to the [[Third Reich]], Kivim\u00e4ki was in a position to observe the anti-Semitic nature of the Nazi regime and the disappearance of German Jews to concentration camps. Kivim\u00e4ki succeeded in reversing Nazi Germany's anti-Finnish stance, obtaining support and favours but at the price of Finland having to form an alliance with Hitler. Finland avoided formal treaties with Nazi Germany up until the [[Ryti-Ribbentrop Agreement]], which was signed after the fall of [[Viipuri]] in June 1944.\n\nSeveral individuals and factors were critical for the [[Winter War]] and the [[Continuation War]]. Kivim\u00e4ki without any doubt occupies a prominent position among pro-Axis Finnish leaders.\n\n==Cabinets==\n* [[Kivim\u00e4ki Cabinet]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|\n title=[[Prime Minister of Finland|Prime&nbsp;Minister&nbsp;of&nbsp;Finland]]|\n before=[[Juho Sunila]]|\n years=1932&ndash;1936|\n after=[[Ky\u00f6sti Kallio]]\n}}\n{{succession box|\n title=[[Minister of Justice (Finland)|Minister&nbsp;of&nbsp;Justice]]|\n before=[[Karl S\u00f6derholm]]|\n years=1931&ndash;1932|\n after=[[Hugo Malmberg]]\n}}\n{{succession box|\n title=[[Minister of the Interior (Finland)|Minister&nbsp;of&nbsp;the&nbsp;Interior]]|\n before=[[Matti Aura (independent)|Matti Aura]]|\n years=1928&ndash;1929|\n after=[[Arvo Linturi]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{FinnishPrimeMinisters}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kivimaki, Toivo Mikael}}\n[[Category:1886 births]]\n[[Category:1968 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Tarvasjoki]]\n[[Category:People from Turku and Pori Province (Grand Duchy of Finland)]]\n[[Category:Finnish Party politicians]]\n[[Category:National Progressive Party (Finland) politicians]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Finland]]\n[[Category:Ministers of the Interior of Finland]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Justice of Finland]]\n