e      = <!--Founded-->\n| established_date       =\n| established_title2     = Incorporated\n| established_date2      = 1968\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n| area_footnotes         =\n| area_total_km2         = 4.72\n| area_land_km2          = <!--See table @ Template:Infobox settlement for details on automatic unit conversion-->\n| area_water_km2         =\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n| population_as_of       = 2006\n| population_footnotes   =\n| population_note        =\n| population_total       = 341\n| population_density_km2 = 72.2\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n| timezone               = [[Pacific Time Zone|PST]]\n| utc_offset             = -8\n| timezone_DST           =\n| utc_offset_DST         =\n| coordinates            = {{coord|50|23|1|N|125|57|37|W|region:CA-BC|display=inline}}\n| elevation_footnotes    = <!--for references: use<ref> </ref>  tags-->\n| elevation_m            = 30\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n| postal_code_type       =\n| postal_code            =\n| area_code              =\n| blank_name             = [[List of British Columbia provincial highways|Highways]]\n| blank_info             = [[British Columbia Highway 19|19]]\n| blank1_name            = Waterways\n| blank1_info            = [[Johnstone Strait]]\n| website                = {{official website|https://www.sayward.ca/}}\n| footnotes              =\n}} <!--Infobox ends-->\n'''Sayward''' is a [[village]] located in the [[Sayward Valley]] on the northeast coast of [[Vancouver Island]] in [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]. It is located about 1&nbsp;mi (1.6&nbsp;km) inland from [[Kelsey Bay, British Columbia|Kelsey Bay]] on a spur from [[British Columbia Highway 19|Highway 19]].  \n\nThe village is named after William Parsons Sayward <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/sayward_william_parsons_13E.html|title=Biography \u2013 SAYWARD, WILLIAM PARSONS \u2013 Volume XIII (1901-1910) \u2013 Dictionary of Canadian Biography|website=www.biographi.ca|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>, a successful lumber merchant from [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]] who was born in Maine in 1818 and came to Victoria from California in 1858.<ref>{{Citation|last=Akrigg|first=G.P.V.|last2=Akrigg|first2=Helen B.|title=1001 British Columbia Place Names|place=Vancouver|publisher=Discovery Press|year=1969|edition=3rd, 1973}}</ref>{{Rp|153}} The 2016 population of the village was 311,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bcstats.gov.bc.ca/StatisticsBySubject/Census/2016Census/PopulationHousing/CensusSubdivisions.aspx?ctl00_ctl00_PlaceholderPageContent_PlaceholderPage3_usercontrols_general_censuscsvviewer_ascx1_CensusCsvGridChangePage=6_50|title=Census 2016: Census Subdivisions - BC Stats|website=www.bcstats.gov.bc.ca|access-date=2017-05-18}}</ref> down from 341 in 2006 and 379 in 2001.<ref>[http://www12.statcan.ca/english/census06/data/popdwell/Table.cfm?T=302&SR=626&S=1&O=A&RPP=25&PR=59&CMA=0 Statistics Canada, 2006 Census]</ref> The village lies off the coast of [[Hardwicke Island]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sayward Valley]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.sayward.ca/ Village of Sayward]\n\n{{VancouverIslandCommunities}}\n{{Subdivisions of British Columbia|village=yes}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Northern Vancouver Island]]\n[[Category:Populated places in the Strathcona Regional District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n| name                   = Sayward\n| official_name = Village of Sayward<ref name=BCmunis>{{cite web|url=http://www.cscd.gov.bc.ca/lgd/infra/library/Name%20Incorp%202011.xls|title=British Columbia Regional Districts, Municipalities, Corporate Name, Date of Incorporation and Postal Address|publisher=British Columbia Ministry of Communities, Sport and Cultural Development|type=[[Microsoft Excel|XLS]]|accessdate=November 2, 2014}}</ref>\n| other_name             =\n| nativ